Analysis of the Global Transition from Fossil Fuels to Renewable and Nuclear Energy from 1990-2014¶

By Angela Liu

Introduction¶

Today, we are constantly reminded of the importance of reducing our reliance on fossil fuels and take up renewable energy to combat global warming. To summarize, renewable energy is energy collected from resources naturally replenished within a human lifetime. Common examples include wind, solar, and geothermal. Fossil fuels are a nonrenewable energy source that are used far more quickly than they are being replenished and burning them release greenhouse gasses that warm up the planet.

Despite hearing about frequent breakthroughs in renewable technology, I wonder how much progress have we actually made and when we can start relying on cleaner energy sources. It is only natural to ask when will we stop stop relying fossil fuels as our primary source for energy? With this online tutorial, I hope to enlighten readers with the truth about energy production.

We will be focusing on 8 major energy sources:

  • solar: solar panels collect sunlight to generate electricity or sunlight is used to heat up water to move turbines
  • wind: targe turbines use wind to turn and generate electricty
  • geothermal: hot rocks deep inside the earth heat up water to produce steam that moves turbines
  • hydropower: moving water turns generators in dams
  • wave/tidal: the kinetic energy of waves and tides is used to produce electricty
  • biomass: organic materials is used for heat and industrial fuel
  • fossil: hydrocarbons(most notably coal, oil, and natural gas) are used as fuel and heating
  • nuclear: nuclear fission creates heat to produce electricity

Gathering Data¶

The data I used come from a large csv file collect by the United Nations from Kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/unitednations/international-energy-statistics along with an Energy Questionare Guideline to help explain the data.

All the other links I will be extracting supporting data from:

https://www.eia.gov/international/rankings/world?pa=12&u=0&f=A&v=none&y=01%2F01%2F2018 for top energy producing countries in 2014

https://www.euronuclear.org/glossary/fuel-comparison/ for metric tons of uranium to kwh conversion

https://extension.psu.edu/calculating-the-green-weight-of-wood-species for volume of wood to metric tons conversion

https://b8f65cb373b1b7b15feb-c70d8ead6ced550b4d987d7c03fcdd1d.ssl.cf3.rackcdn.com/cms/guidance_docs/pdfs/000/000/477/original/CDP-Conversion-of-fuel-data-to-MWh.pdf?1479755175 for other energy conversions

There are too many categories and we only want 7 of them: bio, geo, hydro, nuclear, solar, wave, and wind. However, according to the Energy Questionare Guidelines, most of these categories are variants of fossil fuels and biofuels. To group all these different categories together, I created a new Dataframe 'order', that lists keywords to determine which group each category belong to. I left 'electricity_net_installed_capacity_of_electric_power_plants', 'heat', and 'total_electricity' out because I decided these groups are too broad to be meaningful.

# returns the energy source name of a category for given row index
def get_source(i):
    cat = df4['category'].iloc[i]
    sources = list(order.columns.values)
    if cat in sources:
        return cat
    for s in sources:
        if cat in list(order[s]):
            return s
    return 'fossil'

Our data is in a much simpler form and read to be analyzed. Here are what the columns represent:

  • country: country where energy is produced
  • year: year of recorded production
  • unit: unit of measurement of the given quantity
  • quantity: how much of the energy is produced in given unit
  • source: one of the 8 groups of energy: bio, geo, hydro, nuclear, solar, wave, wind, and fossil
  • category: category of original energy data that gives more specific information about that energy

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Now that we have our data in a nicer form, lets start by looking at energy production trends from 1990-2014 by the top 30 countries. To plot each energy source properly, we first need to make sure that all the data in each source have the same units.

From these lists, fossil, geo, and nuclear have multiple units within them. These units will need to be converted into Kilowatt-hours, million as that is what most of the other energy sources are recorded in. Here, I will assume 'Kilowatt-hours, million' means a million Kilowatt-hours(kwh), which is a Gigawatt-hour(gwh). Similarly, 'Metric tons, thousand' is a thousand Metric tons and 'Cubic metres, thousand' is a thousand Cubic metres.

In [27]:
df5.loc[((df5['source'].str.match('nuclear'))) & (df5['unit'].str.match('Metric Tons'))].category.unique()
Out[27]:
array(['uranium'], dtype=object)

Fixing nuclear is relatively easy as the only category that uses metric ton is uranium. All we need is the converting factor for uranium. This website gives an approximate 45,000 kWh per 1 kg of uranium.

1 kg = 45000 kwh

1 metric ton = .001 kg

1 metric ton = 45,000,000 kwh = 45 gwh

In [28]:
# for each row with source as nuclear and unit as Metric Tons, apply conversion and record unit as kwh, mil
for i in df5.loc[((df5['source'].str.match('nuclear'))) & (df5['unit'].str.match('Metric Tons'))].index:
    df5.at[i,'quantity'] *= 45
    df5.at[i,'unit'] = 'Kilowatt-hours, million'

Fixing bio somewhat harder as there are now 3 different units, each with several different categories. First we need to convert cubic meters, thousand into metric tons, thousand for fuelwood. This website gives an approximate conversion of 1500 kg/m3.

1 m^3 = 1500 kg = 1.5 metric ton

1.5 m^3 = 2.25 metric ton

1.5 m^3 = 2.25e-3 thousand metric tons

In [32]:
# for each row with source as bio and unit as cubic meters, thousand, apply conversion and record unit as metric tons, thousand
for i in df5.loc[((df5['source'].str.match('bio'))) & (df5['unit'].str.match('Cubic metres, thousand'))].index:
    df5.at[i,'quantity'] *= 2.25e-3
    df5.at[i,'unit'] = 'Metric tons,  thousand'

Then we convert all bio in metric tons, thousands to terajoules using conversion found in pdf

1 metric ton = .001 Gg 1 metric ton, thousand = 1 Gg (just need to multiply by TJ/Gg)

Charcoal: (31.05 + 29.5)/2 = 30.275 TJ/Gg

Biogasoline: (28.42 + 27)/2 = 27.71 TJ/Gg

Biodiesels: (28.42 + 27)/2 = 27.71 TJ/Gg

Of_which_biodiesel = 27.71 TJ/Gg

Wood/Wood waste: (16.42 + 15.6)/2 = 16.01 TJ/Gg

Bagasse (and anything else not accounted for): not listed so we take avg of above listed = 25.88 TJ/Gg

for i in df5.loc[((df5['source'].str.match('bio'))) & (df5['unit'].str.match('Metric tons,  thousand'))].index:

    elif df5['category'].iloc[i] == 'charcoal':
        df5.at[i,'quantity'] *= 30.275
    else:
        df5.at[i,'quantity'] *= 25.88
    # units are replaced with TJ
    df5.at[i,'unit'] = 'Terajoules'

Fossil fuels is the trickiest one. There are several categories in metric tons and each has a slightly different conversion to terajoules. Manually converting each one seems impractical so to save time and effort we will average all numerical values in that table. The pdf we just used contains a lot of these categories but as a pdf, webscraping doesn't work very well here either. We want the average conversion factor for all fuel types so we go down to pages 10 and 11 and copy and paste the table directly as a string, ignoring the column titles. Then we split the string by newlines and spaces, and put all floats into a list. The average of all these float values will be our conversion for metric tons to terajoules. First we go down to pages 10 and 11 and copy and paste the table directly as a string. Then we split the string by newlines and spaces, and put all floats into a list. The average of all these float values will be our conversion for metric tons to terajoules.

list1=re.split(" |\n",raw)
# first element is an empty string so get rid of it
list1=list1[1:]

# for each element, add to list2 if converting to float does not cause error
for l in list1:
    try:
        ele=float(l)

# returns tuple containing year, total quantity, and country for given country, year, and source
def get_quantity(country,year,source):
    total = -1   
    data = df5.loc[(df5['country'] == country) & (df5['year'] == year) & (df5['source'] == source)]
    if len(data) > 0:
        if total == -1:
            total = 0
        for d in data.index:
            total += df5.loc[d, 'quantity']

    return year, total, country

Most of these plots present a strong linear trend with the exception of wind. To address that, we could try a polynomial regression. However, which degree should we use?

Machine Learning¶

To tackle this problem, we can use supervised machine learning with holdout cross-validation to select the best degree. I set the training set to be 70% of the wind data and holdout set to other 30%. Then I iterate over a list of degrees ranging from 1 to 9. Any higher higher will be unnecessary for a convex scatterplot with no inflection. For each degree, I train features on the training set by tranforming existing features into a higher degree and fit them into sklearn's Linear Regression. Then I predict on that training set and evaluate how well my prediction performed under the holdout set by extracting the rMSE (square root of the mean squared error). The degree with the lowest rMSE is the best fitted one.

As degree increases, our model becomes more complex and training loss will always decrease. However, generalization loss only decreases up to a point and then start to increase because of overfitting. Not only that, complex models require extremely large coefficients on polynomials. Therefore we want the minimum degree that gives an acceptable performance.

In [49]:
x=[get_total_quantity(i,'wind')[0] for i in range(1990,2015)]
y=[get_total_quantity(i,'wind')[1] for i in range(1990,2015)]
In [50]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X = np.array(x).reshape(-1, 1)
y = y

x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3)

rmses = []
degrees = np.arange(1, 10)
min_rmse, min_deg = 1e10, 0

for deg in degrees:

    # Train features
    poly_features = PolynomialFeatures(degree=deg, include_bias=False)
    x_poly_train = poly_features.fit_transform(x_train)

    # Linear regression
    poly_reg = LinearRegression()
    poly_reg.fit(x_poly_train, y_train)

    # Compare with test data
    x_poly_test = poly_features.fit_transform(x_test)
    poly_predict = poly_reg.predict(x_poly_test)
    poly_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, poly_predict)
    poly_rmse = np.sqrt(poly_mse)
    rmses.append(poly_rmse)
    
    # Cross-validation of degree
    if min_rmse > poly_rmse:
        min_rmse = poly_rmse
        min_deg = deg

# Plot and present results
print('Best degree {} with RMSE {}'.format(min_deg, min_rmse))
        
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(degrees, rmses)
ax.set_yscale('log')
ax.set_xlabel('Degree')
ax.set_ylabel('RMSE')
fig.set_figwidth(13)
fig.set_figheight(8)

Best degree 9 with RMSE 13013.187786830471

From the plot showing the rMSE's of each degree, we can clearly see dramatic improvement from linear to quadratic and then to cubic regressions. However, any higher and we receive diminishing returns. 9 may have the lowerst rMSE(expected since it is the max degree we tested) but 3 seems the most practical. Therefore we choose cubic.

In [51]:
# returns result of cubic polynomial with coefficients a, b, and c for input x
def objective(x, a, b, c, d):
    return (a * x) + (b * x**2) + (c * x**3) + d
In [52]:
from scipy.optimize import curve_fit
from matplotlib import pyplot
from numpy import arange
popt, _ = curve_fit(objective, x, y)

# get coefficients
a, b, c, d = popt
equations['wind']=(a,b,c,d)
# plot input vs output
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.scatter(x, y)
# define a sequence of inputs between the smallest and largest known inputs
x_line = arange(min(x), max(x), 1)
# calculate the output for the range
y_line = objective(x_line, a, b, c, d)

# create a line plot for the mapping function
ax.plot(x_line, y_line, '-', color='red',label='y={:.2f}x+{:.2f}x^2+{:.2f}x^3+{:.2f}'.format(a,b,c,d))
ax.set_title('Total Production of Wind from 1990-2014')
ax.set_xlabel('Year')

ax.legend(fontsize=15)

fig.set_figheight(8)

Using scipy's curve_fit function, we found a cubic function that fits our wind data much more nicely than a linear one.

Hypothesis testing¶

We have our regression equations and they seem to fit very nicely but to make sure of this, we need to do some hypothesis testing. When performing hypothesis testing on a regression line, our null hypothesis will always be all the slope parameters ($\beta _i$) are equal to 0. In other words, will the regression model contain at least one useful predictor? If our p-value is less than our significance level $\alpha$, we will reject the null hypothesis in favor of our alternate nypothesis, which is that the regression model does contain at least one useful predictor. That is what we want to achieve, because it says our model is useful on some level. Otherwise, we fail to reject our null hypothesis. We will be perform this hypothesis testing on each subplot.

$\alpha =0.05$

For wind:

$H_0:\beta _1=\beta _2=\beta _3=0$

$H_a:$ At least one $\beta _i\neq 0$ for $i=1,2,3$

The rest:

$H_0:\beta _1=0$

$H_a:\beta _1\neq 0$

Let's first start with the rest as their linear regressions make hypothesis testing much easier.

Final Question¶

Now that we have analyzed the data sufficiently to get a good idea of what is going on and we have the our regression equations, we will address our beginning question: when will we stop stop relying fossil fuels as our primary source for energy?

To answer this, all we need to do is iterate over years until the sum of all predictions for non-fossil fuel outweigh the prediction for fossil fuels of a given year.

In [56]:
for y in range(2114, 3114):
    total = 0
    for s in sources:
        if s=='wind':
            total+=objective(y, equations[s][0], equations[s][1], equations[s][2], equations[s][3])
        elif s=='fossil':
            total-=equations[s][0]*y+equations[s][1]
        else:
            total+=equations[s][0]*y+equations[s][1]
    if total>0:
        print('Year: '+str(y))
        print('Difference: '+str(total))
        break

Year: 2225
Difference: 10237062.196249485

Based on our current trends, we will break even with fossil fuels in 2225, 224 years from 2021! That may be too late for our planet though...

Conclusions¶

Although 2225 seems alarming, the specific year should not be taken too seriously. The most recent data was given is 2014 and we have certainly made a lot of progress since then. Additionally, the metric ton to kwh conversion with fossil fuels was heavily handwaved and many categories within might not have anything to do with producing energy. Finally, the further we predict into the future, the less accurate our models become. In the real world, we will stop producing energy from fossil fuels as by their nature as nonrenewable energy, we will run out at some point. However, these predictions still reveal how much we as a humanity rely on fossil fuels. If we want improvement in the near future, we must take drastic action immediately.
